Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Defendant appeared in OCCR regarding the bench warrant issued in 22CM1715. Due to the DV modifier listed in count 1, this case will be heard before Judge Havas, Branch 10. Case rescheduled to align with 22CM1715.

Defendant Josiah A Ellis appeared by video.  Attorney Emily Jane Bell appeared by video for Josiah A Ellis.  
Prosecuting attorney Olivia Simmons appeared by video for the State of Wisconsin. 
Deputy Court Clerk: rmm. 
Hearing held via Zoom.  Counsel informed Court there has been a breakdown in communication.  Defense motion to withdraw as counsel is granted by the court. Defendant ordered to contact the Public Defender's Office to see if he qualifies..  Case adjourned for status of counsel in Branch 01.
Status conference scheduled for November 9, 2022 at 03:00 pm.

Court ordered no contact with A.A.T.
No Contact Order, signed and filed.
Court ordered defendant TURNED OVER TO Justice Point for SUPERVISION Level 4. No possession of dangerous weapons or firearms.

Defendant Josiah A Ellis appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney Jade K Hall appeared by video for Josiah A Ellis. Attorney Katrina Voge appeared by video for the State of Wisconsin. Defendant is advised this case is assigned to Judge Davila, Branch 1. Court reviewed the complaint and found probable cause.  Defendant advised of right to counsel and complaint given to defendant's attorney.  Defendant pled not guilty.  DEFENDANT IS INDIGENT AND QUALIFIES FOR PUBLIC DEFENDER REPRESENTATION.
